tree.title: Louisiana Expungement Application (LEA)
tree.description: This app will help you determine whether or not you can get your criminal conviction expunged under Louisiana law.
tree.disclaimer: This app does not provide legal advice. Any information which you give here is not confidential and is not protected by attorney-client privilege.

branch.content: Are you seeking an expungement for a crime that was committed in another state?

Many parishes require your records to process an expungement. Contact the parish clerk of criminal court or {{an attorney}} where you were processed to find out whether the Court requires your records and on how you should proceed.
Do you have a copy of your criminal history?
It is not possible to expunge a record for an offense that was outside of Louisiana. {{Contact an attorney}} in the city in which you were processed for more information and how to proceed.
Were you convicted or plead guilty after your arrest?
How did the prosecution against you end?
branch.fork: A) I was acquitted by a judge or jury OR I filed a Motion to Quash that was successful.

B) The District Attorney refused all charges against me and a Bill of Information was never filed OR the District Attorney dismissed (nolle prossequi) all charges against me after a Bill of Information was filed.
C) I successfully completed a Diversion program

branch.content: Were you convicted of a felony or misdemeanor?
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} on how to proceed and whether you are eligible to have your record of arrest destroyed.

Which of the following sentences describes the sentence for the offense for which you were arrested? See La. Code Crim. Pro. art 571, 571.1, 572, 573.
If you do not understand these phrases, review the statute for which you were arrested as a guide at http://hueylaw. org/site/index.php
branch.fork: A) Necessarily punishable by a term of imprisonment at hard labor.
B) Punishable by a term of imprisonment by a term with or without hard labor
C) Punishable by a fine or imprisonment

branch.content: An arrest that did not result in a conviction typically ends when a District Attorney refuses to prosecute and does not file a Bill of Information against you, the District Attorney dismisses all charges before trial, a judge or jury acquits a defendant, or when a Motion to Quash is successful. {{Seek the advice of an attorney}} to help you understand what may apply to you.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement six (6) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether you should proceed before that time.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement four (4) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether you should proceed before that time.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement two (2) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether you should proceed before that time.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement six (6) months from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether you should proceed before that time.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement thirty (30) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether you should proceed before that time.
Was a true bill filed against you?
Typically, offenses for which there is no time limit for the District Attorney to file charges are ineligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} to determine whether this applies to you.
It may be possible to have your record expunged. Seek the advise of a licensed attorney to review your case.
Did your charge arise out of a domestic violence arrest?
Were you convicted of a crime of violence under La. Rev. Stat. Ann. 14:2?
Were you sentenced pursuant to Louisiana Code of Criminal Procedure article 894B or a deferred sentence in favor of probation?
Did your conviction arise out of an arrest that involved a sexual act?
Under current expungement law, offenses that involved a sexual act may not be expunged. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out whether there is an opportunity for you to overcome this provision.
Were you sentenced pursuant to Louisiana Code of Criminal Procedure article 894B or a deferred sentence in favor of probation?
Did you successfully complete probation? (Your probation was NOT revoked.)
It may be possible to seal your record from public view five (5) years after the completion of your sentence. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out more.
It is likely that you are eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out how your record may be sealed from public view.
It may be possible to seal your record from public view five (5) years after the completion of your sentence.
Did you successfully complete the terms of your probation?

At this time, you are not likely eligible for an expungement until five (5) years has passed from the date you completed your sentence. {{Contact an attorney}} for more details on expungement and destruction of your record.

Which of the following matches the statutory sentence for the arrest or charge against you?
For more information on the sentence, go to Huey Law and review the statutory requirement of sentencing for the arrest or charge against you: http: //hueylaw. org/site/index.php. See also La. Code Crim. Pro. art. 571, 571.1, 572.
branch.fork: A) Necessarily punishable by a term of imprisonment at hard labor
B) Punishable by a term with or without hard labor
C) Punishable by a fine or imprisonment

branch.content: Did the Diversion program arise from a Driving Under the Influence (DUI) arrest?
It is likely you are eligible for an expungement six (6) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out when it is best for you to proceed with an expungement.
It is likely you are eligible for an expungement four (4) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out when it is best for you to proceed with an expungement.
It is likely you are eligible for an expungement two (2) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out when it is best for you to proceed with an expungement.
It is likely you are eligible for an expungement six (6) months from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out when it is best for you to proceed with an expungement.
It is likely you are eligible for an expungement thirty (3) years from the date of the offense. {{Contact an attorney}} to find out when it is best for you to proceed with an expungement.
Was a True Bill filed against you?

When a prosecution has been initiated following a True Bill, there is no time limit to institute formal proceedings. It is likely that you are not eligible for an expungement. {{Consult an attorney}} to review your case.
When a prosecution has failed to secure a True Bill, it may be possible to seal your record from public view. {{Consult an attorney}} to review your case.

Defendants who participate in a Diversion program arising out of a DUI offense are ineligible for an expungement for five (5) years pursuant to La. Rev. Stat. Ann. 15:587.1, State v. Granger, 982 So.2d 779 (2008). {{See an attorney}} to determine whether you may be eligible for an expungement following completion of Diversion for a DUI offense.
You are likely eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} to review the details of your case.
You are likely eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} to review the details of your case.
At this time, you are not likely eligible for an expungement until five (5) years has passed from the date you completed your sentence. {{Contact an attorney}} for more details.

Under Louisiana Code of Criminal Procedure article 893E, crimes of violence are ineligible for deferred sentences, which is required for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} with questions or to find out more information.
Are or were you required to register as a sex offender under La. Rev. Stat. Ann. 15:540 et seq?
You are not likely eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} with questions or to learn more.
Did the offense involve a child under the age of 17?
You are not likely eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} with questions or to learn more.
Were you convicted of distribution or the attempted distribution of a controlled dangerous substance?
Was the charge pursuant to La. Rev. Stat. Ann. 40:976(A), which includes but is not limited to distribution of methamphetamine or cocaine?
Were you convicted before 1995? Edit

It may be possible to expunge this record. To be eligible for an expungement, the defendant MUST meet ALL requirements set forth below:
The conviction was a first offense for distribution under La. R.S. Ann. §40:967A You do not have any convictions after you served the sentence You were not sentenced as a habitual offender You completed intensive incarceration under La. R.S. Ann. §15:574.4 You have no current charges filed against you Nineteen years have passed since the completion of the sentence You have no other felony expungements under La. C.Cr.P. art. 893E
Were you convicted before 1995?
Seek the advice of a licensed attorney to advise you on ex post facto considerations.
Was the conviction your first felony conviction anywhere in the country?
Were you given a deferred sentence in favor of probation pursuant to Louisiana Code of Criminal Procedure article 893E?
You are not likely eligible for an expungement. {{Contact an attorney}} with questions or to learn more.
